An adult child has a moral responsibility to care for their parents. 
| Argüman You can use arrow keys to navigate in the map. 
Loading tree... 
An adult child has a moral responsibility to care for their parents. 
however score: 10 The child-parent relationship must be a just institution. 
A child is not expected to care for an abusive parent. 
sources: Christina Sommers “Filial Morality,” Journal of Philosophy (1986) but score: 4 We did not choose to be born so why should I care about my parents? 
sources: David Archard "Filial Morality" (1996) because score: 2 We are social creatures and must depend on one another for support. 
Without the role expectations of the child-parent relationship we are less capable. 
sources: Aristotle, Sommers because score: 1 The parent-child relationship is the root of self-cultivation and political order. 
The child learns how to act in society and be respectful to others within the family unit. 
Filial piety is thus a core moral concept. 
sources: Kwong-loi Shun “Xiao (Filial Piety)” Encyclopedia of Chinese Philosophy 2003 David B. Wong “Universalism Versus Love with Distinctions,” Journal of Chinese Philosophy 16 (1989), pp. 251-272 David B. Wong “Universalism Versus Love with Distinctions,” Journal of Chinese Philosophy 16 (1989), pp. 251-272 David Archard "Filial Morality" (1996) Mencius via Kwong-loi Shun “Xiao (Filial Piety),” Encyclopedia of Chinese Philosophy (Routledge, 2003). 
